    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Instead of looking at the source code, you should read the javadoc <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#format%28java.lang.String,%20java.lang.Object...%29\" rel=\"noreferrer\">String.format()</a> and <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Formatter.html#syntax\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Formatter syntax</a>.</p>\n\n<p>You specify the format of the value after the %. For instance for decimal integer it is <code>d</code>, and for String it is <code>s</code>:</p>\n\n<pre><code>String aString = \"world\";\nint aInt = 20;\nString.format(\"Hello, %s on line %d\",  aString, aInt );\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Output: </p>\n\n<pre><code>Hello, world on line 20\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>To do what you tried (use an argument index), you use: <code>*n*$</code>,</p>\n\n<pre><code>String.format(\"Line:%2$d. Value:%1$s. Result: Hello %1$s at line %2$d\", aString, aInt );\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Output:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Line:20. Value:world. Result: Hello world at line 20\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
